    <section id="physiological-reset">
      <h2>The Physiological Reset</h2>
      <p>When pre-commitment isn't enough — when the situation is genuinely novel, or when the pressure was unexpected — the fastest path to better decision-making is to first change your physiological state. You cannot out-think a stress response; you can interrupt it.</p>

      <h3>Box Breathing / Extended Exhale</h3>
      <p>Slow, deliberate breathing activates the parasympathetic nervous system through the vagus nerve, counteracting the sympathetic stress response. The most evidence-backed protocol:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Inhale for 4 counts</li>
        <li>Hold for 4 counts</li>
        <li>Exhale for 6–8 counts (the longer exhale is the key — it's what activates the parasympathetic response)</li>
        <li>Repeat 3–5 cycles</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Research by Zaccaro et al. (2018) confirmed that slow-paced breathing with extended exhalation reduces cortisol and subjective anxiety within minutes. Navy SEALs use a version of this (called "tactical breathing") before high-stakes operations.</p>

      <h3>The Strategic Pause</h3>
      <p>In high-pressure decision situations, the single most valuable thing you can often do is introduce a pause. Not an indefinite delay — a deliberate, bounded pause: "I need 15 minutes before I respond to this." "Let me sleep on this before I commit." Even a brief pause allows the acute stress response to partially subside, returning access to prefrontal function.</p>
      <p>The counterintuitive truth: the situations that feel most urgent are often those where a pause is most valuable, because urgency is frequently a feeling created by the emotional state rather than a requirement of the actual situation.</p>

      <h3>Cognitive Reappraisal</h3>
      <p>Reframe the pressure itself. Research by Jamieson et al. showed that telling people "your stress response is helping you prepare" — rather than asking them to suppress stress — actually improved performance under pressure. The physiology doesn't change; the interpretation does. Reappraising arousal as energy rather than threat allows the physiological activation to help rather than hinder performance.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="how-to-apply">
      <h2>How to Apply These Techniques</h2>
      <StepsList steps={[
        {
          title: "Map your recurring high-pressure situations",
          description: "List the 3–5 situations where you most often make decisions under pressure. Be specific: salary negotiations, conflict conversations, market volatility responses, medical decisions, deadline crises. Vague categories produce vague preparations."
        },
        {
          title: "Build pre-commitment protocols for each",
          description: "For each situation, write: 'If [this situation occurs], I will [this specific process].' Include: who you consult, what information you gather before deciding, what criteria you use, and what your default response is if you cannot gather more information."
        },
        {
          title: "Practice the physiological reset now",
          description: "Don't wait for a crisis to try box breathing for the first time. Practice 5 minutes daily until it's automatic. The technique works best when it's a trained habit — not something you're attempting to recall and execute while already under stress."
        },
        {
          title: "Create a 'pause protocol'",
          description: "Decide in advance what you'll say to buy yourself a pause when you feel pressured to decide immediately. A few phrases: 'Let me think about this and get back to you within the hour.' 'I want to give this the consideration it deserves — can I respond by [time]?' Having the language ready reduces the social friction of pausing."
        },
        {
          title: "Debrief after high-pressure decisions",
          description: "Within 24–48 hours of any significant high-pressure decision, review: What did I feel? What did I actually know? Did I follow my pre-commitment protocol? What would I do differently? This debrief builds the pattern recognition that makes future pressure situations more manageable."
        },
        {
          title: "Separate the decision from the emotion with writing",
          description: "When facing a high-stakes choice under pressure, write down: (1) what you actually know, (2) what you're feeling, (3) what your pre-commitment protocol says to do. The act of writing externalizes the problem and reduces emotional contamination of the reasoning process — a technique used by Jeff Bezos, who famously required written memos before any major Amazon decision."
        }
      ]} />
    </section>

    <section id="misconceptions">
      <h2>Common Misconceptions</h2>

      <ContentBox type="warning">
        <h3>❌ "Good decision-makers stay emotionally detached"</h3>
        <p>Damasio's somatic marker hypothesis and decades of neuroscience research confirm that people with damage to emotional processing centers make catastrophically poor decisions — they cannot weight options because nothing feels more important than anything else. The goal is not to eliminate emotion from decisions but to prevent acute stress responses from overwhelming deliberate reasoning. Regulated emotion is a decision asset; flooded emotion is a liability.</p>
      </ContentBox>

      <ContentBox type="warning">
        <h3>❌ "Pressure reveals true character"</h3>
        <p>This romanticizes what is actually a cognitive impairment. Pressure reveals trained habits and pre-committed responses — not some deeper truth about who you are. People who perform well under pressure do so because they've prepared extensively, not because they possess special character. The implication: excellent high-pressure performance is trainable, not innate.</p>
      </ContentBox>

      <ContentBox type="warning">
        <h3>❌ "If you're experienced, pressure doesn't affect you"</h3>
        <p>Experience reduces some pressure effects by building the automatic patterns that bypass deliberation — but it doesn't eliminate the physiological stress response. Even elite operators experience cortisol spikes under threat. What experience provides is better pre-committed protocols, greater pattern recognition, and more practiced physiological regulation — not immunity to the underlying biology.</p>
      </ContentBox>
    </section>

