    <section id="conclusion">
      <h2>Conclusion</h2>
      <p>The brain under pressure is a different organ than the brain at rest — measurably less capable of the deliberate reasoning that consequential decisions require. This isn't a character flaw; it's biology. And like most biological constraints, it responds to preparation.</p>
      <p>The most reliable path to better decisions under pressure runs through the calm periods between crises: building pre-commitment protocols, practicing physiological regulation, developing the pause habit, and debriefing to improve future performance. The goal is to make as few major decisions as possible in real-time under pressure — and to be as prepared as possible for the ones you can't avoid.</p>
      <p>Under pressure, the best decision-makers aren't thinking more clearly than everyone else. They're executing better preparation.</p>
    </section>

    <ContentBox type="tip">
      <h3>Start Before the Next Crisis</h3>
      <p>Pick the one high-pressure situation you face most often. Right now — before you need it — write down your pre-commitment protocol for it. What will you do? Who will you consult? What criteria will you apply? What's your default if you can't get more information? File it somewhere you'll find it when you need it. That document may be the most valuable thing you write this week.</p>
    </ContentBox>

